Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt: Attorney David Celebre is appointed at the repayment rate of $150 per month until the sum is paid. The first payment shall be made on 10/3/2022.

10:31 PM  Attorney Daniel Joseph Tombasco in court for State of Wisconsin. Defendant Deja A. Rucker in court. Clerk N. Nobile.
MINUTES: Court vacates the warrant and reinstates bond. Defendant sworn in. Court finds that the defendant was rejected by the SPD Office. Court orders Attorney David Celebre appointed as advocate counsel; Deft to pay $150/month commencing 10/03/22. Court adjourns. Copy of order appointing counsel mailed to defendant.
Status conference scheduled for October 31, 2022 at 10:00 am.

DE left voicemail for Branch 6 clerk while in court. DE mixed up the dates and believed that her court hearing was scheduled for tomorrow morning. Clerk scheduled VA with DE for 9/21/22 at 10:30 am. DE notified by email.

10:42 AM Attorney Daniel Joseph Tombasco in court for State of Wisconsin. Defendant Deja A. Rucker not in court. Clerk N. Nobile.
MINUTES: Based on the DE's failure to appear, Court issues a bench warrant with a $1,000.00 cash bond. Cash bond on deposit ordered forfeited.
No disposition. Leave on for next scheduled court activity.
